By Monday evening, the renewable energy expert was still fighting to stay in office after spending a night in the Ethics and Anti-Corruption Commission cells, with reports indicating he had been caught red-handed receiving Sh200,000 from a petrol station attendant, according to the EACC. 

While many had expected Mr Oimeke to be arraigned on Monday after spending the weekend in custody, he was released on bond late on Friday. He had then returned to the office and was conducting his duties unperturbed. 






"We were shocked to see him in the office. We had not heard about him after the arrest on Thursday. There were a few people around as well; men dressed in suits and standing outside his office and that of the board chairman. That caused a lot of confusion," a senior manager who requested anonymity intimated. 

Crisis meeting 

The board held a crisis meeting on Friday as Mr Oimeke carried on with his duties at his desk. The board at one point moved the venue of the meeting from the third floor, where Oimeke's office is situated, to the ground floor, and later to the first floor. 

By evening, Mr Oimeke was still making calls to staff members to present the monthly pump prices’ statement for his signature, unaware that they had been instructed not to give the monthly statement to the embattled boss.  



