He left after 4.30 pm, as the pump prices were delayed till after 7pm, by which time a new appointee had been picked to replace him. 

While his first term began quietly – at the height of the 2017 political campaigns – with the exit of engineer Joseph Ng'ang'a (who quietly retired eight months before the expiry of his term in January 2017), his second did not. 

A second petition had been filed to block his second term in office, just weeks to the end of his first term in July. 

Accusations 

The petitioner, Mr Emmanuel Wanjala, accused Mr Oimeke of dragging Epra into massive irregular dealings, including installation of faulty meters and increased court cases against the authority by former employees – who were dismissed for pointing out wrongdoings or mismanagement of resources and abuse of office.  

Through his lawyer Henry Kurauka, the petitioner accused Mr Oimeke of abuse of office, mismanagement of a public institution and public resources, corruption, tribalism and favouritism and wanted his reappointment blocked for not being a member of a relevant professional body as clearly stipulated under section 13 (3) (e) of the Energy Act. 

The EACC had been enjoined in the case with a view to compelling the agency to investigate the claims, but the watchdog said in court that no complaints had been filed against Mr Oimeke before it. 



