In the earlier petition, which was withdrawn under unclear circumstances, the Epra boss had been accused of irregular issuance of licences and appointments that had failed to 'reflect the face of Kenya', with close to 80 per cent of his recruits allegedly hailing from one community. 

A court order issued by Justice Hellen Wasilwa to stop the regulator's board chaired by retired Supreme Court Judge Justice Jackton Ojwang' from renewing Oimeke’s term did not last long. 

Justice Wasilwa would later dismiss the case two months later for lack of evidence, paving the way for Mr Oimeke's return to EPRA where the Corporation Secretary /Director of Legal Affairs Mueni Mutung'a had been appointed to hold brief in his absence. 

Facebook claims deleted 

There was a social media post alleging his connection to powerful political figures who would ensure his return to the office. He, however, deleted the post and his Facebook account after the matter was reported by the Business Daily. 

His return only added to the fear among some staff and stakeholders who would rarely discuss Mr Oimeke, affectionately referred to as "mfalme (king)" by peers and "scorpion" by some industry players who at some point fell victim to his enforcement actions. 



