To his staff, he was the centre of power and information around the office was strictly guarded. Office computers had all USB ports disabled, making emails the only way to send documents and which could easily be tracked, or so they feared. 

Even the government agencies he regulated made indirect complaints about him, including increased approval of Power Purchase Agreements (PPAs) at a time the country was choking from excess generation of electricity and consumers were continuously paying for unused power. 

Kenya Power protested after Epra reportedly allowed some 34 PPAs over a short duration, deals that would inject about 1,891 Megawatts into the national grid in the next five years. 

The electricity distributor wrote to the parent ministry demanding that the energy regulator be removed from Power Purchase Agreement negotiations to reduce oversupply of electricity in the market. 



